photo.description: These two sculptures were probably my favorites from the Altes Museum. They were sculpted approximately 1000 years apart. The one closest to the camera is the older of the two. You might notice that their poses are nearly identical, but the details are subtly different. The older sculpture is considerably more stylized and less realistic. The later pharaoh even has something of a smirk on his face. I find it so hard to fathom a culture that can last thousands of years and have its art be so uniform throughout the millenia. It was truly awe inspiring to stand before these sculptures.

photo.title: Seated Pharaohs

photo.description: Let's get one thing straight. "Caesar" is not a name, it's a title, and it means emperor. We good? Julius Caesar is to be read with a comma: "Julius, Caesar". Emperor Julius. There were over seventy Roman emperors in some form or other throughout the history of 'the Roman empire', so stop saying "seazur" when you mean Julius (who wasn't even called Julius, but Iulius. Without the 'dz' sound at the start. Yes, this is a pet peeve. Just like how English turns Marcus into Marc. Greek, too; Homeros isn't 'Homer'. Oh yeah, and it's Platoon)
photo.tags: altenationalgalerie museum musea nationalgallery berlin painting
photo.title: Ceasar

photo.description: Okay, this work was labelled german realism. Let's review: there's a guy in a suit of armour next to a lion... directly behind this is a naked guy, with some keys, luring what appear to be women dressed in curtains Even further back still there is a woman, naked, doing something with a fountain. I'm not going to psycho-analyse that, but I think it's safe to say that this is perhaps not *the* most realistic depiction of germany... or just realistic depiction, for that matter.
photo.tags: altenationalgalerie museum musea nationalgallery berlin painting
photo.title: German... realism?
